{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:15:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16891"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16891"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.03,0.16,0,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67872"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16891"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53337"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"524"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5131"},{"type":"tags","id":"8471"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22725"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67872"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProton pump inhibitors are commonly prescribed medications used in the management of acid-related disorders in the upper digestive tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes their primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibition of gastrin release from G cells","Direct neutralisation of stomach acid","Blockade of histamine H2 receptors on parietal cells","Reduction of acetylcholine release from vagal nerve endings","Irreversible inhibition of hydrogen/potassium ATPase enzyme"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe aim of this class of agents is to reduce gastric acid secretion. Proton pump inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eirreversibly inhibiting the hydrogen/potassium ATPase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E (proton pump) in gastric parietal cells. These drugs are prodrugs that become activated in the acidic environment of the secretory canaliculi, where they covalently bind to and inhibit the proton pump, blocking the final common pathway of acid secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits gastrin release from G cells\u003C/strong\u003E: proton pump inhibitors do not directly affect gastrin secretion or G cell function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutralises stomach acid directly\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of antacids, whereas proton pump inhibitors prevent acid production rather than neutralising existing acid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks histamine H2 receptors on parietal cells\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of histamine H2 receptor antagonists such as ranitidine, which is a different class of acid suppressants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces acetylcholine release from vagal nerve endings\u003C/strong\u003E: proton pump inhibitors do not affect neurotransmitter release or neural signalling pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy inhibiting the proton pump, these medications effectively reduce gastric acid production regardless of the stimulatory signal (histamine, gastrin, or acetylcholine).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Proton pump inhibitors irreversibly inhibit the hydrogen/potassium ATPase enzyme in gastric parietal cells.","Inhibition of the proton pump reduces gastric acid secretion by blocking the final common pathway of acid production.","Proton pump inhibitors are prodrugs that require activation by acid in the secretory canaliculi of parietal cells."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53337"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16891"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53337"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T16:00:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T16:01:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9581"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67872"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t